<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-055-204 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 328 265</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Sept 23 1991 v25 n38 p89(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>VARs: hard to find and harder to rate. (information systemsdepartments use value-added resellers for software and service)(Marketplace)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Radding, Alan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Information systems (IS) departments increasingly find benefits byusing value-added resellers (VARs) to provide service and softwarefor microcomputers, workstations and networks.andP;  IS managers likeVARs instead of major suppliers because often VARs are moreflexible.andP;  However, selecting VARs and comprehending the servicesprovided can be a challenge.andP;  Not all VARs are able to work wellwith big IS organizations because they do not have the staff andfinancial resources to meet the organizations' needs.andP;  Inaddition, many retailers use the title VAR, so it is important toinvestigate what value-added offerings are provided.andP;  Generally, aVAR provides training, software and support.andP;  Good places toconnect with VARs include trade shows or by word-of-mouth.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MISSupport ServicesTrainingThird-Party VendorsValue-added resellersInformation systemsComputer RetailingComputer Services.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>